# Abstract {#abstract}

**Trust is the fundamental positive multiplier of our problem-solving capacity**, making it crucial for addressing global challenges such as climate change, environmental protection, nuclear proliferation, and resource depletion.

We propose an **Intuitive Trust-Building Framework** grounded in **epistemic impartiality**, the unbiased pursuit of knowledge, **moral** **impartiality**, and the equitable treatment of all. At its core are six trust traits: **Reliability**, **Cognitive Empathy**, **Intellectual Humility**, **Honesty**, **Future Orientation,** and **Moral Character**. Cultivating these traits and corresponding **observable behaviors** helps individuals and groups to accelerate trust-building and cooperate more effectively with each other.

To operationalize this framework, we introduce an **Authentic Networking Platform**. On it, users validate the authenticity of their connections and endorse each other’s **trustworthy behaviors**. A **modified PageRank algorithm** analyzes these endorsements, quantifying the trustworthiness of individuals and the memetic fitness of their ideas. This method deters manipulation, incentivizes genuine trustworthiness, and grants trustworthy actors an **evolutionary advantage**.

The proposed Intuitive Trust-building Framework can help **bridge divides** across cultures and **enhance our collective problem-solving capacity**. **Widespread adoption** of the Authentic Networking Platform can accelerate progress toward a more **cooperative**, **resilient**, and **ethically grounded** global society.

# Introduction to The Problem {#introduction-to-the-problem}

“*We have the wisdom to make the best use of talents we have from birth and the privilege of controlling and directing our own mind to purposes of our choice*” —  
 Adapted from Napoleon Hill

For readers unfamiliar with the **evolutionary dynamics of** **trust**, we recommend engaging with the interactive simulation at [https://ncase.me/trust/](https://ncase.me/trust/). This resource offers an accessible introduction to how **environmental factors**, **repeated interactions**, and **communication constraints** influence the emergence and sustainability of **trust**.

## Trust: The Fundamental Multiplier {#trust:-the-fundamental-multiplier}

**Trust** is the fundamental positive **multiplier** of collective **problem-solving capacity**. The evidence decisively validates this claim:

**First, trust enables three essential capabilities:** knowledge creation, knowledge sharing, and the collective pursuit of long-term goals. No other factor—neither intelligence, resources, nor technology—enables all three simultaneously (Sperber & Mercier, 2017; Van Lange et al., 2013).

**Second, history proves trust's decisive role.** The Montreal Protocol succeeded because **nations trusted each other** enough to act collectively, phasing out 98% of ozone-depleting substances. This action protected the ozone layer and averted an estimated **2 million skin cancer cases annually** (UNEP, 2023). In contrast, the Kyoto Protocol failed due to mistrust between developed and developing nations, resulting in **12.5 gigatons of additional CO2 emissions**—an ecological cost equivalent to **planting 70 trees for every person on Earth** (IPCC, 2021).

**Third, trust uniquely works across all scales**—from individual relationships to entire societies—creating a **compounding effect** that no other factor can match. It empowers people to overcome local challenges and tackle global ones equally effectively (Nowak & Sigmund, 2005).

**Fourth, trust transforms zero-sum into positive-sum cooperation.** Game theory demonstrates that trust allows competing parties to shift from **self-serving** strategies to prioritizing mutual benefit. This transformation unlocks collective potential, fostering cooperation in critical areas like free trade, environmental agreements, and global health initiatives (Axelrod, 1984; Ostrom, 1990).

**Fifth, trust alone has the potential to solve three fundamental challenges to human progress:** the Hard Problem of Cooperation (aligning individual and collective interests) (Axelrod, 1984), the Tragedy of the Commons (protecting shared resources) (Ostrom, 1990), and the Tragedy of Rationality (enabling collective rationality) (Mercier & Sperber, 2017).

Consequently, **mistrust** is the fundamental **negative multiplier** of collective **problem-solving capacity.** This realization is **alarming**, as trust is declining across the board—not only among friends, neighbors, workplaces, and societies but also in institutions, governments, media, and corporations (OECD, 2024; Pew Research Center, 2024).

Current global challenges are more significant, complex, and dangerous than ever. These include **climate change, nuclear proliferation, pandemics, and the alignment of artificial intelligence**—problems that demand unprecedented levels of global coordination and trust (IPCC, 2021; United Nations, 2023). Without an increase in our collective problem-solving capacity—or worse, if it continues to decline—**humanity faces a genuine risk of extinction.**

Deutsch (2011) argues that **mistrust is solvable**, as no problem permitted by the laws of physics lies beyond the reach of knowledge. Building **trust begins at the individual level:** if individuals become **more trustworthy**, their relationships, organizations, and broader societies—right up to nations and global systems—will inherently become more trustworthy, too (Wilson, 2015; Nowak & Highfield, 2011).

## The Hard Problem of Cooperation {#the-hard-problem-of-cooperation}

The **Hard Problem of Cooperation** is the challenge of fostering cooperation between agents—**individuals** or **groups**—where each can gain at the expense of others. Each agent pursuing their **own interests** often leads to **collective failure**. (Eriksson & Strimling, 2012).

The Hard Problem of Cooperation is best illustrated by the **Prisoner’s Dilemma**. Two agents must choose to **cooperate** or **defect**. Defection gives the highest **individual payoff**, but mutual cooperation provides the best **collective outcome**. The dilemma shows how **individual interests** can erode collective success and highlights the need for **trust** to align personal and collective goals (Axelrod, 1984). 

The Hard Problem of Cooperation is driven by three barriers that make it systematically challenging to achieve cooperation. 

The first barrier is the **appearance of trustworthiness without substance**. Those who fake trustworthiness often gain rewards while avoiding the costs of trustworthy actions, which disadvantages truly trustworthy individuals or groups.

For example, the prevalence of **fake reviews in online marketplaces** exemplifies how superficial trust signals systematically outcompete genuine trustworthiness, disadvantaging honest actors. A *World Economic Forum* report estimated that fake reviews influence **$152 billion** in global e-commerce spending annually, skewing purchasing decisions and undermining fair competition (WEF, 2021). Research in *Marketing Science* highlights that sellers purchasing fake reviews gain higher visibility and sales, placing ethical competitors at a structural disadvantage (Mayzlin et al., 2022). These findings underscore how systematic failures inadvertently amplify **appearing trustworthy** over **being trustworthy**, enabling untrustworthy behavior to dominate. 

Similarly, politicians who **fake their trustworthiness** often outperform those who are actually trustworthy. Krupnikov and Piston (2020) found that candidates using **emotional appeals** gain voter trust more effectively than those relying on substantive policy arguments. Lewandowsky et al. (2017) showed that repeated exposure to emotional rhetoric enhances perceived trustworthiness, as voters prioritize **familiarity and emotional resonance** over factual accuracy. The *Electoral Integrity Project* (2017) further highlights how **populist leaders** manipulate trust by presenting themselves as anti-establishment "outsiders," leveraging emotional narratives rather than verifiable records to gain support. These findings collectively underscore how **perceptions of trustworthiness**, shaped through emotional and strategic appeals, often dominate over genuine integrity in political competition.

The second barrier is the focus on **short-term rewards** over **long-term trustworthiness**. Short-term-oriented actors gain immediate benefits without paying upfront costs, while long-term-oriented actors bear costs now in the hope of larger future rewards.

For example, during the 2008 financial crisis, banks and financial institutions prioritized **short-term profits** through risky subprime lending and mortgage-backed securities, leading to a housing bubble and eventual market collapse. These short-term actors reaped massive immediate gains but destabilized the financial system. In contrast, more minor, conservative banks that maintained **trustworthy lending practices** and avoided high-risk investments faced losses and limited growth during the bubble, as they could not compete with the short-term gains of their riskier competitors (Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission, 2011; Reinhart & Rogoff, 2009).

Similarly, in workplace collaborations, freelance platforms like **Upwork** or **Fiverr** often feature **short-term actors** who cooperate only when it brings immediate benefits, such as accepting projects, delivering **minimal viable work**, and moving on without investing in relationships. In contrast, **long-term-oriented freelancers** who sacrifice time to build trust, provide **exceptional quality**, and foster ongoing partnerships often lose out due to **mistrust** from clients whose cost to validate genuine trustworthiness is prohibitively high. Studies show that clients frequently choose **cheaper, short-term freelancers** over **reliable, higher-quality ones**, creating a cycle where **trust is undermined** and **transactional relationships dominate** (*Lehdonvirta et al., 2018; Graham et al., 2017*).

The third barrier stems from the **confidence-competence paradox**: those who know less tend to be more confident, while true experts often express more caution (Kruger & Dunning, 1999). This creates a systematic problem because humans instinctively trust confident voices (Tversky & Kahneman, 1974). We use displayed confidence as a mental shortcut—a **heuristic**—to judge expertise, even though research consistently shows that confidence poorly predicts actual competence (Smith et al., 2019; Roediger & DeSoto, 2014).

This misalignment creates a destructive **feedback loop** in society. Less competent individuals display unwarranted confidence. Their confident demeanor attracts trust. This misplaced trust leads to their promotion and increased influence. **Social institutions**—from media to leadership structures—amplify their reach by rewarding confident voices over accurate ones. The cycle continues as genuine expertise, typically expressed with appropriate caution and nuance, gets systematically overlooked.

For example, during the COVID-19 pandemic, research by MIT Sloan tracked 126 million social media posts about COVID-19, finding that **false claims spread 70% faster** than accurate information due to more confident language (Yang et al., 2021). The WHO InfoDemic Project found that accounts expressing the highest confidence in their claims had only **28% accuracy** yet maintained trust ratings **3.2 times higher than cautious** expert sources (WHO, 2022). This systematic bias led 64% of Americans to trust confident, definitive sources over scientifically cautious ones, even when previous predictions proved wrong (Gallup/Knight Foundation, 2021).

Similarly, in the domain of **financial advice**, a study of investment newsletters tracked 153 market forecasters who made explicit predictions. Those expressing the highest confidence gained 45% more subscribers despite having a 28% lower prediction accuracy (Graham et al., 2020). The SEC Investor Protection Study found that clients consistently rated highly confident advisors as **more trustworthy,** even when their portfolios **underperformed** the market by an average of 12% (SEC, 2021). This misplaced trust cost investors an estimated $43 billion in suboptimal investment decisions over a five-year period (CFA Institute, 2022).

## The Tragedy of the Commons {#the-tragedy-of-the-commons}

The **Tragedy of the Commons**, as described by Hardin (1968), occurs when individuals overuse **public goods** or shared resources for personal gain, depleting them for everyone. Each person acts rationally in their own short-term interest, but collectively, this behavior leads to resource collapse, harming all. Ostrom (1990) showed that **trust** and strong local institutions can prevent this by ensuring cooperation and fair use. Without **trust**, individuals fear others will exploit their restraint, leading to widespread overuse and eventual disaster.

For example, in **climate change**, nations delay reducing emissions, fearing others will **free-ride** on their sacrifices. **Coal-dependent economies** hold back unless significant emitters like the **U.S.** and **China** act first. Despite agreements like the **Paris Accord**, unmet pledges and shifting timelines erode **trust**. No one wants to bear the cost alone and be the "**fool**" who sacrifices while others benefit. However, this hesitation makes everyone worse off as **rising sea levels**, **extreme weather**, and **ecosystem collapse** intensify (**IPCC, 2021**).

Another example is **environmental protection** in the **fast fashion industry**, where **competition** prevents pollution reduction. Global brands like **H\&M, Zara, Shein**, and **Forever 21** prioritize **low costs** and rapid production, pressuring suppliers to cut corners. In **Bangladesh's Dhaka district**, textile factories discharge **untreated dye wastewater** into the **Buriganga River**, turning it black and killing fish (Islam et al., 2020). In **Xintang, China**, manufacturers pollute rivers with **lead** and **mercury**, harming local health (Ma et al., 2019). Indonesia’s **Citarum River**, contaminated by **microplastics** and chemicals, is one of the world’s most polluted waterways (Ismail et al., 2021). No single actor wants to bear **cleanup costs** alone—if a supplier invests in **water treatment**, production costs rise, and competitors pollute cheaply. Brands like **Zara** face a dilemma: enforce strict standards and lose to **Shein**, which ignores them (Brydges et al., 2021). This results in a **race to the bottom**, with **local communities** suffering from poisoned rivers and soils (Uddin et al., 2017). Without **trust** and **accountability**, responsible actions feel futile, and everyone—**polluters included**—loses in the long run.

## The Tragedy of Rationality {#the-tragedy-of-rationality}

Steven Pinker (2011) describes the **Tragedy** **of** **Rationality** as a subset of the **Tragedy** **of** **the** **Commons**. Pinker suggests that collective rationality is a **public** **good**, much like forests, oceans, or the climate, and is essential for the well-being of us all. The Tragedy of Rationality occurs when actions rational for agents—individuals or groups—lead to irrational outcomes for the collective. 

Humans evolved to favor their own group—**kin**, **neighbors**, **tribe**, or **community**—while distrusting **outsiders**. Outsiders are those from other groups who don’t share the same ties, culture, or identity. Without mechanisms to treat outsiders as equals, we exploit them when the benefits outweigh the risks. We **cheat**, **break promises**, or even **kill**—actions we wouldn’t tolerate within our own group. This feels **rational**: protect your own and take advantage of outsiders. But when every group acts this way, **trust** between groups erodes. 

On a global scale, conflicts like **Russia's 2022 invasion of Ukraine** highlight the dangers of nuclear proliferation. If Ukraine is attacked because it lacks nuclear weapons, it signals that **nuclear deterrence ensures survival.** This could lead Ukraine to **consider developing nuclear weapons**, even under constraints, and spark a **chain reaction.** Countries like **South Korea** and **Japan**, facing nuclear-armed neighbors, might rethink their non-nuclear policies. **Saudi Arabia**, observing instability in the Middle East, could advance its nuclear ambitions. As more nations build arsenals, **mistrust deepens**, and the risk of catastrophic war rises. This is the **tragedy of rationality**: actions that feel rational for one nation when mirrored globally, **make everyone less secure.**

In contrast, **trust** can unite groups, foster cooperation, and prevent conflict. When groups build **mutual trust**, they reduce the need for defensive actions like **arms races** and open the door to solving shared problems. **Trust** creates **stability**, promotes **peace**, and enables **progress**—turning zero-sum competition into **collective gain**.

## Why We Disagree on What Is Right and Wrong {#why-we-disagree-on-what-is-right-and-wrong}

Building trust is challenging, both within groups (kin, friends, neighbors, community, nation) and with **those outside these groups**—individuals or entities that are not part of the immediate social, cultural, or political circle. The core challenge lies in the lack of universal agreement on **right and wrong** (morality) or **true and false** (epistemology). This creates unresolved moral and epistemic conflicts, which erode trust.

Various ethical frameworks, such as **utilitarianism** and **deontology**, have been proposed to resolve moral disputes. However, neither is universally accepted, as they struggle to reconcile differences in **moral foundations**.

* **Utilitarianism**, which aims to maximize well-being, faces challenges when groups disagree on whose well-being matters most or how to define harm.  
* **Deontology**, which prioritizes absolute rules, struggles when those rules conflict across cultures. For example, one culture’s emphasis on free speech may clash with another’s focus on preventing harm or preserving dignity.

Haidt (2012) explains that different cultures prioritize different **moral foundations**—such as fairness, loyalty, or sanctity. These foundational values shape ethical perspectives and often lead to seemingly irreconcilable disagreements. For instance, focusing on **individual rights** may conflict with **collective well-being** or **traditional norms**. While moral foundations theory helps explain these differences, it lacks tools to resolve them. The result is that, so far, philosophers, scientists, and spiritual leaders have been **unable** to propose a **universal normative ethics framework** capable of bridging cultural and societal divides.

## Why We Disagree on What Is True and False {#why-we-disagree-on-what-is-true-and-false}

Trust often involves deciding which ideas are **true** and which are **false**. For non-experts, resolving **epistemic conflicts**—disagreements about the validity of ideas—requires significant effort. Complex topics like **climate policy**, **AI regulation**, **migration**, or **trade agreements** demand expertise, time, and reliable evidence. Most people lack these resources, making it difficult to evaluate ideas quickly and cost-effectively. Instead, we rely on **intuition**, **group narratives**, or **ideological biases**, leaving many conflicts unresolved.

**Memetics** (Dawkins, 1976\) explains how ideas spread. **Memes**—units of cultural information—compete based on their **fitness** or ability to replicate and thrive in human minds. Many ideas spread not because they are true but because they are **emotionally compelling**. For example, climate misinformation exploits fears about economic costs, even when it contradicts scientific evidence. Similarly, the idea that life improves if all migrants are deported thrives on oversimplified narratives that resonate emotionally but distort facts.

False ideas sometimes achieve **short-term high memetic fitness**, spreading rapidly. However, **long-term memetic fitness** tends to correlate with utility and truth. For instance, the idea that gravity pulls objects downward persists because it is valuable and true, while the idea that the Earth is the center of the universe has faded because it is false. It is rare for an idea with negative utility to persist for millennia.

Thus far, **science** has not developed a method to measure the **long-term memetic fitness** of ideas. Without tools to **predict** which ideas are likely to **spread** and **endure** over time, many **epistemic conflicts** remain unresolved. This lack of agreement on the **long-term usefulness** of ideas makes **trust-building** difficult. When individuals and societies cannot agree on which ideas are **true**, **trust erodes**, and **cooperation falters**, particularly in environments dominated by **misinformation** and **polarization** (Mercier & Sperber, 2017; Pinker, 2018).

## Toward a Measurement Instrument for Cognitive Trustworthiness {#toward-a-measurement-instrument-for-cognitive-trustworthiness}

What if the **trustworthiness of individuals** could be measured as easily as time or distance? Today, we lack a reliable tool to measure **trustworthiness**, leaving fake appearances to triumph over substance. Such an environment rewards those who **deceive** or **manipulate**, while those who act with integrity are disadvantaged. Short-term gains take precedence as individuals exploit shared resources and prioritize fleeting rewards over lasting commitments. Without mechanisms to ensure **trustworthiness** across cultural or group boundaries, mistrust festers, leading to **exploitation**, **conflict**, and **broken promises**. Meanwhile, humanity remains divided over unresolved **moral** and **epistemic conflicts**, unable to unite against existential threats like climate change, nuclear proliferation, and pandemics. The cost of this mistrust is clear: **progress stalls**, and opportunities for collaboration are lost.

Currently, technologies like lie detectors have significant limitations—they are costly, **one-dimensional**, and focus narrowly on detecting deception rather than measuring the broader concept of **trustworthiness**. No tool exists that can reliably, accurately, and cost-effectively assess trustworthiness in all its dimensions. While creating such a tool is an ambitious project, it is achievable; no fundamental laws of physics prevent its development. By focusing on **observable trust-building behaviors**, such a tool could identify and reward trustworthy individuals, granting them greater **opportunities**, stronger **collaborations**, and increased **influence**. The existence of an accurate, cost-effective, and accessible measurement instrument of trustworthiness would encourage a cultural shift, reducing **mistrust** and **conflicts**, resolving **moral** and **epistemic** disputes, and fostering **cooperation** on global challenges like **climate change** and global **security**. Such a measurement instrument has the potential to unite individuals, groups, and ultimately humanity as a whole in pursuit of a safer, more harmonious world.

# Literature review {#literature-review}

## Indirect Reciprocity {#indirect-reciprocity}

Scholars have extensively analyzed the nature of cooperation—how it works, why it fails, and how it can be improved. Early research focused on evolutionary mechanisms. **William Hamilton** (1964) introduced **kin selection**, explaining how altruistic behavior toward relatives ensures genetic survival. **Robert Trivers** (1971) expanded this with **reciprocal altruism**, showing that repeated, mutually beneficial exchanges foster cooperation even between unrelated individuals. **Robert Axelrod** (1984) demonstrated through game theory how strategies like *tit-for-tat*—cooperating first and reciprocating others’ actions—build trust and sustain collaboration over time. **Elinor Ostrom** (1990) studied real-world examples, finding that trust and locally enforced rules help communities manage shared resources and avoid overuse.

Building on these foundations, **Martin Nowak** identified five mechanisms that drive cooperation: **kin selection, direct reciprocity, indirect reciprocity, network reciprocity,** and **group selection.** Nowak defines **indirect reciprocity** as cooperation based on reputation, where individuals act to enhance their reputation, knowing others will observe and reward them with future opportunities. Unlike direct reciprocity, which depends on repeated exchanges between the same individuals, indirect reciprocity scales trust across larger, more complex networks. In *SuperCooperators* (2011), Nowak argues that indirect reciprocity represents the **greatest untapped potential for fostering large-scale cooperation**. He supports this claim with mathematical models showing that cooperation thrives when reputations are accurate and widely shared and with experiments demonstrating that **observable behaviors** increase cooperation. Nowak concludes that indirect reciprocity is "**the key to the evolution of cooperation in large and complex societies**."

The success of indirect reciprocity depends on several factors. First, **observability** ensures that actions are seen and can contribute to reputation. Studies such as **Milinski et al. (2002)** show that cooperative behavior increases significantly when individuals know their actions are visible. Observability alone, however, is not enough. Observers must be credible and capable of transmitting reputational knowledge. **Nowak and Sigmund (1998)** modeled the importance of reliable observers who can accurately propagate reputations, ensuring that observed actions lead to trust within larger networks.

Second, **spreading and accessing reputational knowledge** efficiently is critical. Reputation systems must allow information to be stored and shared cheaply, ensuring trust scales effectively. **Nowak and Sigmund (2005)** suggest gossip, digital reputation systems, or other low-cost mechanisms help maintain cooperation in large populations. If the cost of spreading or accessing reputational knowledge is too high, reputations remain localized, limiting their effectiveness. Accessible systems, such as reviews, **endorsements,** or shared feedback in digital environments, act as low-cost proxies for spreading and verifying reputations.

Even when observability and spreading mechanisms are in place, a critical vulnerability remains: **the accuracy of reputational information.** **Derek Parfit** (1984) highlights this dilemma in *Reasons and Persons*. He argues that individuals can exploit reputation systems by **appearing trustworthy** without being genuinely trustworthy. By projecting fake trustworthiness, individuals can access agreements and cooperation while secretly exploiting others' trust to gain benefits. This strategy rewards manipulation over sincerity, destabilizing trust-based systems.

While Parfit does not propose a solution, this critique highlights the need for protection against cheating when thinking about creating an **accurate measurement instrument of trustworthiness.** If reputations reliably reflect ethical behavior rather than appearances, the advantages of manipulation diminish. Accurate measurements would align reputations with trust-building actions, ensuring that systems reward individuals for their genuine trustworthiness. This makes cooperation **fairer, safer**, and more sustainable, fostering trust and equity in human relationships. By addressing the vulnerabilities, an accurate measurement instrument of an individual's trustworthiness could transform indirect reciprocity into a robust mechanism capable of scaling trust across diverse groups and interconnected societies.

## Two Cognitive Systems {#two-cognitive-systems}

The **System 1 and System 2** framework describes two complementary systems of human cognition. **System 1** operates **intuitively** and **automatically**, generating rapid responses informed by **heuristics**, **emotions**, and learned routines. It excels in familiar, low-stakes environments where quick judgments are advantageous. However, it struggles with unfamiliar or complex situations. **System 2**, in contrast, is **slower** and more **deliberate**, engaging in effortful reasoning to address abstract or challenging problems. Together, these systems shape how individuals perceive others, process differences, and resolve conflicts, making their interaction essential for understanding **mistrust**.

Research by **Kahneman and Tversky** revealed that humans often rely on mental shortcuts, known as **heuristics**, to simplify decisions. While efficient, these shortcuts can lead to predictable errors. For example, **anchoring bias** occurs when individuals rely too heavily on initial information, while **availability bias** causes people to overestimate the likelihood of events based on recent or vivid memories. Such findings challenged the traditional view of humans as purely rational decision-makers, forming the foundation for **behavioral economics**. **Mercier and Sperber** extended this work by showing that **System 2** not only solves complex dilemmas but also justifies or overrides **System 1** intuition in socially nuanced contexts, highlighting the **adaptability** of human reasoning.

The inherent tension between **System 1** and **System 2** stems from their different evolutionary purposes. **System 1**, optimized for **speed** and **survival**, excels in routine tasks that rely on emotion and experience. **System 2**, designed for abstract and reflective thinking, handles problems requiring **deliberation**. This tension explains why emotional, **intuitive** responses often dominate in moments of conflict or uncertainty while reasoned deliberation struggles to intervene. For instance, an instinctive **moral response**, such as avoiding harm, may conflict with **utilitarian reasoning** that seeks the greatest good for the greatest number. Bridging **trust gaps** requires harmonizing emotional **intuitions** with deliberate reasoning. Recognizing these dynamics is vital for navigating socially complex situations.

## The Gap in Debiasing {#the-gap-in-debiasing}

**Cognitive biases** are predictable errors in **judgment** that arise from the brain’s reliance on **System 1 heuristics**—**mental shortcuts** designed to process information quickly. These shortcuts, while efficient, often lead to **mistakes** in **complex** or **unfamiliar situations** (Tversky & Kahneman, 1974). **Biases** are universal, affecting everyone regardless of **intelligence** or **education**. Over **200** have been identified, highlighting how deeply they influence **moral** and **rational reasoning** (Gigerenzer & Todd, 2002).

**Biases** play a significant role in shaping judgments. **Confirmation bias** causes people to seek out information that supports their **beliefs**, making it harder to evaluate **opposing views** objectively (Nickerson, 1998). **Myside bias** leads individuals to interpret **ambiguous evidence** in ways that favor their side, fueling **conflicts** and **polarization** (Baron, 2008). **Naive realism** makes people believe their perceptions are purely **objective**, which can block understanding between groups and escalate **ideological divides** (Ross & Ward, 1996). These biases distort **individual judgments** and **social interactions**, creating barriers to **cooperation** and **balanced decision-making** (Iyengar & Hahn, 2009).

The origins of **cognitive biases** lie in **evolution**. Early humans relied on **System 1** to make **fast decisions** in **life-threatening situations**. These mental shortcuts allowed them to assess **threats**, **opportunities**, and **social dynamics** quickly, enhancing **survival** (Gigerenzer & Todd, 2002). While effective in **simple environments**, the same mechanisms can lead to errors when dealing with **moral** or **epistemic problems**, where careful **reasoning** is required.

Despite their drawbacks, **biases** persist because they were **adaptive** in the environments where humans evolved. Their continued influence reflects the **evolutionary trade-off** between **speed** and **accuracy** in decision-making. While they often simplify **everyday choices**, their limitations become apparent when they distort **moral reasoning** or hinder **rational problem-solving** in modern settings.

Despite extensive research cataloging **cognitive biases** and their effects on human judgment, relatively little has focused on **debiasing techniques** themselves (Arkes, 1991; Larrick, 2004). A **PsycInfo search** (Nov 13, 2024\) shows **27,979 results** for “**cognitive bias**” compared to only **474 results** for “**debiasing**”.

Most debiasing methods rely on System 2 to **override** System 1, shifting from automatic, heuristic processing to controlled, rule-based thinking (Stanovich & West, 2000; Epstein, 1994; Kahneman, 2003). However, Lilienfeld et al. (2009) argue that **these methods are often ineffective** because they require significant time, cognitive effort, and resources. Instead, they suggest that effective debiasing should target **System 1** directly, making decision-making faster, more intuitive, and accessible while reducing cognitive demands. Therefore, **debiasing** is essential for **trust building** because if **biases persist**, it becomes harder to agree and, **therefore, more challenging to trust** each other.

## Evolution of Morality   {#evolution-of-morality}

System 1 can be understood through two main domains: **automatic intuitions** and **automatic actions**:

* **Automatic intuitions** include rapid evaluations shaped by pattern recognition, associative thinking, and emotional responses. These processes enable snap judgments, such as social evaluations or **moral judgments**, but they also introduce biases when heuristics are misapplied (Sloman, 1996; Haidt, 2001; Greene et al., 2001). Feelings of certainty and basic needs, such as hunger or safety, further influence these intuitive processes (Damasio, 1994; Panksepp, 1998).  
* **Automatic actions** refer to reflexive behaviors driven by instincts, habits, and immediate decisions. Instincts, such as the fight-or-flight response, are evolutionarily hardwired for survival, while habits represent learned routines that reduce cognitive effort (LeDoux, 1996; Graybiel, 2008). Even decisions often occur reflexively, shaped by System 1’s evaluations and refined by System 2 when necessary (Kahneman, 2011).

**Moral judgments**, a core function of **System 1**, allow individuals to make rapid, **emotion-driven evaluations** about what is right and what is wrong. These judgments—shaped by our collective needs—are essential for maintaining **social cohesion** and **group cooperation** (Haidt, 2001; Keltner & Haidt, 2003). Frans de Waal (1996) observed similar behaviors in **non-human primates**, such as **reconciliation** and **mutual aid**, suggesting that **moral judgments** have deep evolutionary roots. Morality enhances **group harmony** and the **mutual benefit** of the collective.

From an evolutionary perspective, morality likely emerged as a tool to foster **cooperation** and minimize **conflict** within early human groups. Humans relied on **shared resources**, **coordinated defense**, and **social order** to survive. Jonathan Haidt (2001) proposed that **moral intuitions** evolved **before language**, enabling early humans to align their actions through **shared emotions** and **instincts**. Michael Tomasello and colleagues (2005) expanded on this by describing "**shared intentionality**"—a uniquely human capacity to **synchronize goals** and collaborate in ways non-human primates cannot. **Empathy**, **reciprocity**, and **fairness** became crucial for building **trust** and fostering **group cohesion**, aligning **individual interests** with the **collective good** (Trivers, 1971; Sober & Wilson, 1998).

Early approaches to **moral psychology** focused heavily on **individual reasoning** but missed broader, **cultural dimensions** of morality. **Kohlberg (1969)** emphasized a **justice-based framework**, proposing that **moral development** follows **universal stages** centered on **justice** and **fairness**. Yet his framework struggled to explain **cultural variations** in **moral judgments**.

In the late 1970s, cultural anthropologist **Richard Shweder** set out to answer a fundamental question: Is **morality universal**, or is it shaped by **culture**? Immersing himself in **India**, Shweder observed **moral judgments** that often diverged from **Western ideals** of **individual rights** and **autonomy**. In these communities, moral debates focused less on **harm** and more on **respect for social roles**, **communal obligations**, and **purity**. Through extensive interviews and observations in **Orissa**, Shweder and his colleagues found that moral thinking often prioritized values like **family loyalty**, **tradition**, and the **sacred** over individual autonomy.

This evidence led Shweder to conclude that **morality** is not a universal concept but one shaped by distinct **cultural domains** (Shweder, Much, Mahapatra, & Park, 1997). From this research emerged three key ethics: **Autonomy** (individual rights and freedoms), **Community** (social roles and responsibilities), and **Divinity** (purity and spiritual sanctity). Shweder’s model reshaped **moral psychology**, challenging **Western-centric assumptions** and highlighting the **cultural diversity** of **moral thought**.

Building on **Shweder’s** insights into culturally shaped moral domains, **Jonathan Haidt** sought to bridge cultural and universal moral values through an **evolutionary** lens. He introduced the **Moral Foundations Theory**, positing that humans possess innate "**moral taste receptors**" that attune them to particular moral intuitions across cultures. Similar to how taste receptors on the tongue help us detect essential **flavors**, our “moral taste receptors” evolved to address social needs crucial to human groups, helping individuals navigate complex social dynamics.

Haidt’s six foundational "**flavors**" include **Care/Harm**, **Fairness/Reciprocity**, **Loyalty/Ingroup**, **Authority/Respect**, **Purity/Sanctity**, and **Liberty/Oppression** (**Haidt**, 2012). Each foundation serves a distinct **social function** shaped by evolutionary pressures: **Care** promotes **empathy**, **Fairness** supports **justice**, **Loyalty** fosters **group cohesion**, **Authority** respects **hierarchy**, **Purity** upholds **sanctity**, and **Liberty** resists **oppression**. These foundations illustrate how **evolutionary** and **cultural** factors embed diverse moral sensitivities within us, equipping individuals with intuitive responses to various social challenges. While Haidt’s model describes these moral inclinations, it acknowledges that individuals might navigate these intuitions differently as they mature, and **cross-cultural** influences further shape how these foundations are emphasized. 

**Haidt (2012)** and **Leslie Newson (2017)** assert that religion evolved as a **cultural adaptation** to enhance **group cooperation**. Through **rituals** and **shared beliefs**, religion strengthened **group identity**, enabling large societies to function cohesively. Newson’s research found that **religious communities** often outperformed non-religious ones in **population growth** and **resilience**, as **rituals**, **moral teachings**, and **shared norms** built **trust** and reinforced **group cohesion**.

Haidt (2012) defines moral systems as “interlocking values, virtues, norms, practices, identities, institutions, and psychological mechanisms that work together to suppress or **regulate self-interest** and make cooperative societies possible.” Comparing this definition to the Hard Problem of Cooperation—**overcoming short-term self-interest** to achieve long-term goals—reveals a complementary relationship. Moral systems historically addressed the Hard Problem of Cooperation by **building** **trust** within **close-knit communities**. This raises a critical question: how can moral systems evolve to accelerate **trust-building**, cooperation, and conflict resolution on a **global scale** despite **differences** in moral foundations **between groups**?

While Shweder and Haidt’s models reveal universal moral foundations that resonate across cultures, they fail to address how to reconcile differences when these foundations come into conflict. Haidt advocates for a **pluralistic approach** to morality, acknowledging that moral values vary significantly across cultures and individuals, shaped by distinct social, historical, and environmental contexts. This diversity challenges the idea that a universal **normative ethical framework** can be found. Haidt views it skeptically, stating, “*I don’t know what the best normative ethical theory is for individuals in their private lives*” (Haidt, 2012). Instead of pursuing a universal normative ethical framework, this perspective highlights the need for an **Intuitive Trust-building Framework**—one that bridges diverging moral foundations and fosters cooperation despite conflicting moral foundations.

## Evolution Of Reasoning  {#evolution-of-reasoning}

While **System 1** enables rapid, intuitive judgments, **System 2** introduces **reasoning**, a slower, more deliberate process for **analytical thought**. **Reasoning** allows individuals to evaluate evidence, solve problems, and articulate complex ideas, facilitating cooperation and adaptation to novel challenges.

Reasoning, traditionally seen as the hallmark of rationality, is now understood as a **social tool**. Mercier and Sperber (2011) argue it evolved primarily for **persuasion**, **self-justification**, and **group coordination**. Anthropological research supports this, suggesting that reasoning helped early humans establish **norms**, manage relationships, and foster **cooperation** that was critical for survival (Cosmides & Tooby, 1989; Tomasello, 2010). Reasoning likely co-evolved with **language**, enabling humans to address the challenges of larger social groups by refining verbal exchanges and promoting effective **collaboration** (Pinker, 1994). Beyond **intuition**, reasoning added **reflection**, facilitating problem-solving and thriving in complex social environments.

Richard Dawkins' **memetic theory** (1976) provides **an insightful explanation of the role of reasoning** in human evolution. Dawkins proposes that ideas, or "**memes**," spread through **imitation** and evolve like genes. These **memes**—beliefs, practices, or technologies—shape human decision-making and cultural adaptation. Reasoning is the **internal mechanism** that interacts with these **memes**, testing, combining, and refining them to align with individual goals or group **norms**. By manipulating **memes**, reasoning facilitates the exchange and evolution of ideas, driving both individual understanding and societal progress. In this sense, reasoning is not only a tool for **social coordination** but also a cognitive filter that determines which **memes** thrive, influencing the trajectory of cultural evolution.

Daniel Dennett (1995) emphasized that memes undergo a **selection process**, with those that resonate most profoundly surviving in culture. Susan Blackmore (1999) expanded on this by proposing that memes replicate within the **human mind**, shaping **behavior** and **cognition** as they evolve. 

When encountering a new idea, the mind initially relies on **System 1 thinking**—a fast, intuitive process shaped by heuristics and habits—to quickly judge if the idea feels true. If it passes this initial test, **System 2 thinking**—a slower, deliberate process—engages, comparing the idea against existing beliefs. Ideas already stored in the mind are advantageous because they align with the **mental framework**. Conflicting ideas trigger **cognitive dissonance** (Festinger, 1957), which the mind resolves by rejecting the idea, adjusting beliefs, or reconciling the conflict.

In **evolutionary theory**, fitness refers to an organism’s survival and reproduction; in **memetic theory**, fitness describes an idea’s ability to survive, replicate, and spread. Ideas already accepted are often seen as “fit,” though this can lead to **dogmatic thinking**, where entrenched beliefs resist change. For instance, a deeply held belief in God might assign low fitness to contradictory ideas, rejecting them to avoid **cognitive dissonance**. Fitness reflects an idea’s **adaptive value**, correlating with its relevance and usefulness—e.g., nuclear energy has high fitness for meeting energy needs, whereas mammoth hunting does not.

**Steven Pinker** (2018) argues that humanity is gradually converging on a set of **ideas we hold as true**, such as **justice**, **equality**, and **human rights**, driven by the spread of ideas that foster **cooperation** and **well-being**. He cites historical trends—declining violence, expanding civil liberties, and global movements for democracy—as evidence of **high-fitness ideas** shaped by Enlightenment principles of **reason**, **science**, and **humanism**. Over time, high-fitness ideas that enhance our **collective prosperity** tend to spread, while harmful and low-fitness ideas, like slavery and colonialism, are abandoned.

Despite these insights, there is **no comprehensive method to measure an idea’s** **fitness**—its ability to survive and replicate in real-world contexts. Existing frameworks focus on abstract models, leaving a gap in practical tools for evaluating how ideas endure over time.

Platforms like **Metaculus** and methods like **Superforecasting** (Tetlock & Gardner, 2015\) approximate the **fitness of ideas** by using crowd-sourced predictions, but they only measure outcomes tied to observable events. Many ideas—such as **Einstein’s theories** or ethical principles like **human rights**—do not depend on discrete events for their relevance. This limitation leaves societies reliant on **subjective judgment**, increasing the risk of spreading momentarily popular ideas with **low long-term fitness**. Without objective mechanisms to measure the **long-term** **fitness** of ideas, cultural evolution may favor trends that are appealing or persuasive in the short term but fail to contribute meaningfully to societal resilience or progress.

The **long-term fitness** of ideas is critical because it directly influences our ability to acquire **valuable knowledge** and solve **real-world problems**. Misjudging an idea’s fitness can lead to preventable mistakes, such as adopting **low-fitness ideas** or dismissing **high-fitness ones**. For example, the rejection of **vaccines** due to misinformation has cost lives, while the denial of **climate change** delays essential action. Meanwhile, **robust ideas**—such as transitioning to **renewable energy**—often struggle to gain widespread acceptance. Developing a method to measure the **fitness** of ideas could accelerate the adoption of valuable concepts and accelerate trust-building.

# Theoretical Foundation {#theoretical-foundation}

## Distinguishing Moral and Epistemic Impartiality {#distinguishing-moral-and-epistemic-impartiality}

**Impartiality** is a core **ethical principle** that demands treating individuals equally and fairly without **bias**, **favoritism**, or **prejudice** (Rawls, 1971). However, in many existing **ethical frameworks**, **impartiality** is often treated as a single, universal **moral ideal** without sufficiently exploring how it operates in **epistemic contexts**. For example, **utilitarianism** assumes **impartiality** as universal, applying equally to all beings without distinguishing its role in evaluating **knowledge**, **evidence**, and **truth** (Singer, 2011). This **universalist approach** implies a broader applicability, suggesting potential relevance in the **epistemic domain**. For the purpose of creating an Intuitive **Trust-Building Framework**, we believe it’s essential to distinguish between:

* **“Moral impartiality”** involves treating all individuals equally regarding moral considerations, ensuring fairness and justice in ethical treatment. This principle underpins various ethical theories, including utilitarianism, which advocates for the equal consideration of all individuals' interests.   
* In contrast, we propose defining “**epistemic impartiality”** as the consistent application of the same standards to evaluate the memetic fitness of ideas and the trustworthiness of individuals or information sources, irrespective of biases, personal preferences, or affiliations. It ensures that judgments about knowledge claims are made fairly for oneself and for others, using objective criteria. 

To ensure the Trust-building Framework is intuitive, we propose starting with the widely accepted and easy-to-understand **Golden Rule**: “*Treat others as you wish to be treated*.” Its **familiarity** and **simplicity** make it accessible and engages **System 1** thinking (intuitive and automatic processes). Widely recognized across cultures and traditions, the Golden Rule embodies **fairness** and **reciprocity**, capturing the essence of **moral impartiality**. The **Golden Rule** can be found in:

* **Christianity**: "Do to others what you would have them do to you" (The Bible, Matthew 7:12)  
* **Islam**: “None of you truly believes until you wish for others what you wish for yourself.” (Sahih Muslim 1:73)  
* **Buddhism**: "May all beings be happy; may all beings be free from suffering." (Metta Sutta)  
* **Judaism**: "Love your neighbor as yourself." (The Torah, Leviticus 19:18)  
* **Hinduism**: "Do not do to others what you do not want to be done to yourself." (Mahabharata, Anusasana Parva 113\)  
* **Human Rights**: "Respect for others’ dignity and fairness reflects the essence of human rights." (Universal Declaration of Human Rights, Article 1\)  
* **Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union**: Every person has the right to have his or her affairs handled impartially, fairly, and within a reasonable time by the institutions, bodies, offices, and agencies of the Union. (Article 41\)

Critiques of the **Golden Rule**, such as **Nietzsche’s** concept of “**slave morality**” (Nietzsche, 1887\) and **Shaw’s** observation that “*do not do unto others as you would that they should do unto you*” because “*their tastes may not be the same*” (Shaw, 1903), question its **practicality** but **not its validity**. Across cultures, most children learn the Golden Rule early in life, and by adulthood, it is often **intuitively understood**—deeply rooted in **System 1 thinking**: fast, automatic, and emotionally resonant (Kahneman, 2011).

While Haidt classifies the Golden Rule under the **Fairness/Cheating** foundation (Haidt, 2012), evidence suggests it transcends this category. If it were limited to fairness alone, individuals with stronger fairness intuitions **would show more significant agreement** with it. Yet, the Golden Rule is universally accepted across cultures, religions, and traditions, regardless of variations in fairness intuitions.

However, interpretations of the Golden Rule vary indeed. Those with more substantial fairness intuitions tend to apply it **universally**, extending it to out-groups, while those with weaker fairness intuitions often limit its application to **in-groups** (Henrich et al., 2010).

Thus, the Golden Rule cannot be confined to the Fairness/Cheating foundation. Instead, it bridges multiple moral foundations, making it a robust and universal principle for **accelerating trust-building** between individuals and societies.

The **Golden Rule**, while foundational in morality, lacks the precision needed to address complex **epistemic conflicts**. This is why we propose to further ground the trust principles in **epistemic impartiality** and the relevant mechanisms:

* **Reasoning**: Facilitates alignment of diverse perspectives, resolves disagreements, and builds shared understanding through structured argumentation (Mercier & Sperber, 2011).  
* **Scientific Method**: Provides a systematic approach for testing hypotheses, addressing uncertainties, and validating claims (Popper, 1959).  
* **Information Theory and Error Correction**: Together, these ensure accuracy and reliability by distinguishing relevant signals from noise and identifying and addressing inaccuracies in data and arguments (Shannon, 1948; Hamming, 1950; Shor, 1995).

## Proposed Definitions of Trust {#proposed-definitions-of-trust}

Trust has been studied across **psychology**, **sociology**, **economics**, and **organizational studies**. Existing definitions focus on traits like **benevolence**, **competence**, and **predictability** (Mayer et al., 1995; McKnight & Chervany, 2000). These definitions are valuable but often describe trust in **neutral or cooperative settings**. They do not address how to resolve **mistrust**, especially when it arises from **moral differences** or **epistemic conflicts**.

To resolve mistrust, trust definition must include **moral impartiality**—the fair treatment of all—and **epistemic impartiality**—the unbiased pursuit of knowledge. These dimensions are missing in current definitions (Mayer et al., 1995; Johnson & Grayson, 2005). Without impartiality, trust cannot bridge moral and epistemic divides.

We borrowed **Cognitive Trust** and **Affective Trust** from Johnson and Grayson (2005) and introduced **Competence-Based Trust** as an additional category. Our redefinition ensures that trust is equipped to address the root causes of mistrust and fosters cooperation across diverse perspectives. Below are our proposed definitions:

* **Definition: “Cognitive Trust”** enables individuals and groups to overcome short-term self-interest and uncertainty to achieve mutual long-term goals. It emerges through **direct observation of behaviors**, **exchanges of ideas**, and **indirect reputational signals** spread through record systems or gossip. By combining these data points, individuals infer trust-building traits—grounded in **epistemic impartiality**, the unbiased pursuit of knowledge, **moral** **impartiality**, and equitable treatment of all. Trust-building traits are sustained by **shared values, norms, institutions**, and reputational platforms that regulate self-interest and enable cooperation. To better embody trust-building traits, one must acquire relevant knowledge through **conjectures, criticism, and acknowledging one’s fallibility**.  
* **Definition: “Affective Trust”** arises from benevolence, **emotional bonds**, **shared experiences**, and **perceived care**. It reflects **similarities**, **compatibility**, **sympathy**, **past history**, and **mutual sacrifices** that establish **felt obligations of goodwill**. While it can exist alone, it remains more **stable** and **enduring** when supported by Cognitive Trust.  
* **Definition: “Competence-Based Trust”** emerges from **confirmed competence** and **reliable performance**. It emerges through observed **skills**, **results**, and processes followed. Though it can stand independently, it becomes more **durable** when strengthened by Cognitive Trust.

**Cognitive Trust** provides the **foundation**, **Affective Trust** deepens **emotional bonds**, and **Expertise-Based Trust** confirms **capability**. Together, they help individuals and groups sustain cooperation and pursue their shared long-term goals.

* **Definition: “Cognitive Trustworthiness”** is a capacity to inspire Cognitive Trust. It emerges from embodying trust-building traits grounded in **epistemic impartiality**—the unbiased pursuit of knowledge—and **moral impartiality**—the equitable treatment of all. By displaying these trust-building traits through observable behaviors, an individual gains a reputation as a trustworthy actor. A group that makes it difficult for individuals to appear trustworthy without genuinely being so overcomes the short-term self-interests of its members more effectively. Consequently, this group gains an evolutionary advantage because its members are more likely to achieve their mutual long-term goals.

To improve readability, in the following, when we use the word “**trust**”, we actually mean “**Cognitive Trust**”, and when we use the word “**trustworthiness**”, we actually mean “**Cognitive Trustworthiness,**” as per the definitions provided above.

# Methodology {#methodology}

## Developing the Trust-Building Framework {#developing-the-trust-building-framework}

This work began as a practical response to challenges in **communication**, **innovation**, **team collaboration**, and **stakeholder relationships** within our business. Inspired by Ray Dalio’s *Principles: Life and Work* (2017), we systematically documented our most significant mistakes—particularly in **hiring decisions** and **partner selection**—and distilled them into actionable trust guidelines to prevent recurrence. Initially spanning three pages, these principles were refined over several years into six concise, practical rules. The refinement process was **iterative** and **collaborative**, drawing on feedback from **investors**, **advisors**, **team members**, and **candidates** during hiring. Guided by Kahneman’s System 1 and System 2 framework, the resulting theoretical design explains how trust can bridge differences in **moral values** (System 1\) and **epistemic beliefs** (System 2).

The **Golden Rule** offers aspirational ethical guidance but is not always feasible or desirable, particularly in interactions with out-groups or when mutual trust is lacking. To address this, we pair it with the **Silver Rule**: “*Do not treat others in ways you would not like to be treated.*” Together, these rules form a **dual-layered ethical framework**:

* **Golden Rule (In-Group):** Guides aspirational behavior when mutual reciprocity is expected.  
* **Silver Rule (Out-Group):** Sets a baseline to prevent harm even when reciprocity is uncertain.

Using this combined framework, we derive the trust principles through the following structured approach:

1. **Trait:** We identify the core trait (e.g., Reliability) and demonstrate its universality with references to cross-cultural, ethical, and psychological studies.   
2. **Behavior:** We define an observable behavior (e.g., keeping promises) that exemplifies the trait and can be measured or demonstrated.  
3. **Intuitive appeal across cultures**: Based on initial validation and referenced studies, we argue that people across diverse cultures intuitively and consistently prefer interacting with individuals who embody the given trust trait and demonstrate the corresponding observable behavior.  
4. **Grounding in epistemic impartiality**: We align the identified trait (e.g., reliability) with well-established epistemic mechanisms, such as reasoning, scientific method, and information theory with error correction.  
5. **Grounding in moral impartiality:** We provide two contrasting behaviors involving Person A and Person B:  
   * Person A demonstrates observable behavior, following the Golden Rule.   
   * Person B demonstrates the opposite behavior, violating the Silver Rule. 

   To illustrate, below is a **meta-example** that applies the **Golden Rule** and **Silver Rule directly** without focusing on a specific behavior. Please consider whether the following statement is ‘**true**’ for you. 

| Statement 0: All else being equal, person A is more worthy of your trust than person B: Person A treats you in the way she wants to be treated herself. Person B treats you in the way she doesn’t want to be treated herself. |
| :---- |

6. **Trust Principle:** We conclude by defining the trust principle in two of its aspects:  
   * **Golden Aspect (In-Group):** Aspirational behavior to follow the Golden Rule with insiders of the group.  
   * **Silver Aspect (Out-Group):** Harm-preventing behavior adhering to the Silver Rule, particularly with outsiders of the group

## Visualizing Trust Dynamics {#visualizing-trust-dynamics}

To explore trust dynamics and their underlying trust traits, we use visualizations to represent individuals and their interactions. Each **individual** is depicted as a **circle** and a **heart.**

![][image1]

* The **circle** represents **System 2**, which includes deliberate thinking, reasoning, and knowledge. **System 2 holds ideas**—concepts an individual believes to be true. Inside the circle, we represent these ideas as smaller circles, symbolizing the knowledge and beliefs an individual consciously reasons about (e.g., "Idea A is true").  
* The **heart** represents **System 1**, encompassing intuitive processes such as quick pattern recognition, heuristics, and **moral foundations**. Moral foundations influence judgments about right and wrong and are a key part of System 1\.

We use visualizations to illustrate how trust between individuals is influenced by **ideas** (what individuals consider true or false) and **moral foundations** (what individuals consider right and wrong). For example, individuals with similar ideas and moral foundations are more likely to agree and trust each other, while significant differences can lead to disagreements and distrust. To simplify the visualizations, we moved the circle (**System 2**) and heart (**System 1**) visually closer to each other to represent a person’s figure. 

To map trust dynamics, we focus on three roles:

1. **Analyzed Person** **A/B**– the individual whose trustworthiness is being evaluated.  
2. **Group Insider** – an individual **belonging** to the same group or community as the analyzed person  
3. **Group Outsider** – an individual **outside** the analyzed person’s group or community.

![][image2]

Typically, the **Analyzed Person** is likelier to trust a **Group Insider** who shares similar ideas, values, culture, and beliefs. In contrast, it’s a natural reaction from an Analyzed Person to mistrust a **Group Outsider** who significantly differs from her. 

![][image3]

Similarities and differences between represented individuals in our visualizations are conveyed through colors:

* The **red color** of the Group Insider's "mind" and "heart" visualizes the similarity between the analyzed person and the group insider, reflecting their agreements in both moral and epistemic domains.  
* The **black color** of the Group Outsider's "mind" and "heart" visualizes the difference between the analyzed person and the group outsider, reflecting their disagreements in both moral and epistemic domains.

## Hypothesis to Assert {#hypothesis-to-assert}

We aim to show that the following two hypotheses make intuitive sense for people across cultures:

* **Hypothesis 1:** Person A demonstrates adherence to the Golden Aspects of the trust principles, while Person B violates the Silver Aspects of these principles, which makes Person A more worthy of trust for both Group Insiders and Group Outsiders.  
* **Hypothesis 2:** A Group Outsider who consistently adheres to the Silver Aspects of all six derived trust principles is more worthy of trust to the Analyzed Person than a Group Outsider who demonstrates partial or no adherence to the Silver Aspects of these principles.  
* **Hypothesis 3:** A Group Outsider who consistently adheres to the Golden Aspects of all six derived trust principles is more worthy of trust to the Analyzed Person than a Group Insider who does not consistently adhere to the Golden Aspects of these principles.

In the following, we will analyze two scenarios:

1. **Person A** demonstrates an **observable behavior** consistent with following the **Golden Rule** in interactions with her **Group Insider**.  
2. **Person B** demonstrates an **observable behavior** that **violates** the **Silver Rule** in interactions with a **Group Outsider**.

# Theoretical Results {#theoretical-results}

## Deriving Six Trust Traits {#deriving-six-trust-traits}

### Principle 1: Reliability through Keeping Promises {#principle-1:-reliability-through-keeping-promises}

1. **Trait:** Reliability is essential for trust. It reflects consistency in fulfilling obligations and meeting expectations, combining moral integrity with practical dependability (Costa & McCrae, 1992).   
   ![][image4]  
2. **Behavior:** Promise-keeping operationalizes reliability, directly contributing to trust-building (Restatement (Second) of Contracts, 1981). Empirical studies show that reliability fosters trust across cultures and contexts (Rotter, 1967; Gneezy, 2005; Bornhorst et al., 2010). Promise-keeping, viewed as both a moral obligation and a legal duty, promotes social cooperation. In contract law, breaking promises incur legal consequences (Rawls, 1971). Ethics and law underscore reliable behavior as crucial for maintaining social and legal stability.  
   ![][image5]  
3. **Intuitive appeal across cultures:** Across cultures, **promise-keeping** and **reliability** are universally valued. Gneezy (2005) found that honoring promises sustains **trust** across settings, while Bornhorst et al. (2010) showed that fulfilling promises fosters **cooperation**. Fischbacher and Föllmi-Heusi (2013) highlighted **honesty**, including promise-keeping, as central to global social interactions. This universal value arises from promise-keeping's role in aligning **beliefs** with **actions**. **Reliability** builds trust by ensuring commitments are met, while **inconsistency** erodes it and hinders systemic improvement (Covey, 2006; Mayer et al., 1995).  
4. **Grounding in epistemic impartiality:** Reliability is the foundation of predictable, dependable results, similar to ensuring consistent outcomes in computation. It embodies the principle that processes when repeated under the same conditions, produce the same results. This parallels **deterministic systems** in computer science and **error-free computation**, where consistency is key to trust and functionality (Turing, 1936; Shannon, 1948). Without reliability, a system cannot be considered robust.  
5. **Grounding in moral impartiality:** please consider whether the following statement is “true” for you. ### Principle 2: Cognitive Empathy through Active Listening  {#principle-2:-cognitive-empathy-through-active-listening}

1. **Trait**: Cognitive empathy is the ability to understand another person’s thoughts, emotions, and perspectives without necessarily sharing their feelings. It involves perspective-taking and mental state recognition, enabling effective social interactions (Shamay-Tsoory et al., 2009; Baron-Cohen & Wheelwright, 2004).   
2. **Behavior**: Cognitive empathy involves understanding another person’s thoughts and emotions, manifesting behaviorally through Active Listening. It is achieved by demonstrating attentiveness and understanding. Active Listening is observable through behaviors such as assumption checking (Baldwin, 1987), reflecting feelings (Hutchby, 2005), and paraphrasing (Weger et al., 2010, 2014). These actions signal to the speaker that their perspective has been accurately understood.  
   ![][image6]  
3. **Intuitive appeal across cultures:** Active Listening is universally valued for fostering understanding and reducing miscommunication (Imhof & Janusik, 2006). Studies consistently show that behaviors demonstrating attentiveness and empathy, such as paraphrasing and reflecting emotions, build trust and strengthen relationships across cultures (Gearhart & Bodie, 2011). This widespread appreciation for Active Listening highlights its role as a universal expression of cognitive empathy, essential for effective communication and connection in any context.

![][image7]

4. **Grounding in epistemic impartiality:** Active Listening reduces communication errors by mitigating “noise,” such as distractions and biases, that distort messages (Shannon, 1948; Harvard Graduate School of Education, 2017). By reducing noise, it draws from information theory, improving the clarity and reliability of communication. It supports reasoning by fostering mutual understanding and resolving disagreements through focused engagement (Mercier & Sperber, 2011). Active Listening also aids in error correction by identifying and addressing misunderstandings in real-time, ensuring the accuracy of shared information (Hamming, 1950). Furthermore, it complements the scientific method by facilitating a clear and precise exchange of hypotheses and data, which is essential for testing and validation (Popper, 1959).

### Principle 3: Intellectual Humility through Critical Thinking {#principle-3:-intellectual-humility-through-critical-thinking}

1. **Trait:** Intellectual humility is the willingness to acknowledge the limits of one’s knowledge and the openness to new ideas or evidence, even when it challenges one’s beliefs (Kant, 1784; Davis, 2017). It involves recognizing that one’s understanding may be incomplete or flawed, fostering a readiness for learning and growth (Leary et al., 2017).  
   ![][image8]  
2. **Behavior:** Critical thinking is the process that individuals with intellectual humility engage in to evaluate and refine their understanding. **McPeck (1981)** defines Critical Thinking as the **propensity and skill to engage with reflective skepticism**, emphasizing questioning and evidence evaluation. **Paul and Elder (2006)** define it as **disciplined, self-directed thinking**. **Lipman (1988)** focuses on its **evaluative nature**, calling it **skillful, responsible thinking** that is **self-correcting** and **context-sensitive**. **Halpern (1998)** emphasizes its role in **cognitive flexibility and adaptability**, enabling sound **decision-making** in complex situations. 

![][image9]

3. **Intuitive appeal across cultures:** Research such as Bailin et al. (1999) and the Social Axioms Survey (Leung & Bond, 2004), which examines universal beliefs across cultures, shows that Critical Thinking is recognized and valued globally in diverse educational and cultural contexts. Similarly, Kleinsasser et al. (2021) found that intellectual humility, an essential aspect of Critical Thinking, is appreciated across educational settings in multiple countries. This universal appreciation likely arises because Critical Thinking ensures reliable information processing, emphasizing falsifiability and challenging cognitive biases to reduce internal errors.  
4. **Grounding in epistemic impartiality:** Intellectual humility and Critical Thinking are crucial for practical knowledge construction because they reduce errors in processing. Critical Thinking is essential for reasoning because it enables individuals to evaluate arguments, identify flaws, and construct well-supported conclusions (Mercier & Sperber, 2011). Critical Thinking is also at the core of the scientific method because it guides the process of forming hypotheses, testing predictions, and analyzing results rigorously (Popper, 1959). In information theory, it aligns with the process of distinguishing signals from noise (Shannon, 1948). Finally, in error correction, Critical Thinking is similar to how systems use redundancy checks, such as parity bits, to detect and correct internal errors (Hamming, 1950).

Piaget (1932) viewed truth-telling as a key aspect of moral development, where children learn to distinguish between true and false information. Kohlberg (1981) linked honesty to moral reasoning, suggesting that truth-telling evolves as individuals progress through stages of moral development. (2019) surveyed 60 societies worldwide and identified honesty as one of seven universal moral traits, demonstrating that truth-telling and avoiding deceit are globally recognized as essential for cooperation. This universal appreciation likely arises because honesty and transparency are foundational for social harmony and trust.   
4. **Grounding in epistemic impartiality:** Systems, both computational and human, rely on feedback loops to correct errors and improve outcomes (Wiener, 1948). Transparency is key in these processes, enabling others to assess and critique outputs. In reasoning, transparency allows for aligning perspectives and resolving disagreements through open argumentation (Mercier & Sperber, 2011). The scientific method relies on transparency in publishing data and methodologies, ensuring research is open to scrutiny and replication (Popper, 1959). Information theory distinguishes relevant signals from noise, optimizing the feedback process by allowing only valuable insights to be evaluated (Shannon, 1948). Transparency is essential for error correction as it enables external evaluation and facilitates the identification and correction of errors (Hamming, 1950; Shor, 1995).

4. **Grounding in epistemic impartiality: Future orientation** and **long-term thinking** align with the scientific method's emphasis on ongoing testing and falsification attempts even when evidence appears confirming (**Popper, 1959**). **Future orientation** drives the continuous refinement of hypotheses and the pursuit of new evidence, preventing premature conclusions. **Future Orientation** reduces unpredictability, akin to minimizing "noise" in information theory, enhancing focus and consistency in goal-directed actions (**Shannon, 1948**).
