## Key Requirements For Authentic Networking Platform {#key-requirements-for-authentic-networking-platform}

We defined six key trust traits and behaviors. Next, we outline the key requirements for a trustworthiness measuring instrument: reliability, accuracy, cost-effectiveness, and scalability.

### How To Prevent Cheating {#how-to-prevent-cheating}

Cheating becomes easy when **fake profiles** can be created or are challenging to detect. **Trustworthy endorsements** rely on authentic actions tied to **real people**, but fake profiles undermine this by fabricating endorsements and distorting trust. To prevent manipulation, **robust identity validation** is essential. A **social graph** is particularly effective for this, as it maps how interconnected users are through **mutual connections**.

We define an “**authentic connection**” as mutual recognition of each other’s **name** based on the question: *Would you both recognize each other’s name?* **Names**, not faces, were chosen because **reputations** are tied to names, which can be communicated and shared. **Faces**, while identifiable, are not central to trustworthiness.

This **name-based validation** of the connection’s (relationship) authenticity makes it difficult for **fake profiles** to infiltrate the system. **Fake accounts** remain isolated, lacking **mutual connections** with genuine users. If a fake profile establishes connections to **poorly connected** or **untrustworthy profiles**, its **distance** from the **real** **profiles** known by a trusted user will expose its inauthenticity. Furthermore, obtaining validation from **highly** **reputable** **users** would be nearly impossible, ensuring that **the cost of creating a fake profile** that appears trustworthy is prohibitively high. 

### Peers Reward Each Other with Revocable “True” Endorsements  {#peers-reward-each-other-with-revocable-“true”-endorsements}

We propose a system in which **users** **endorse** **each** **other** **based on their** **adherence** **to** **trust** **principles**. Here, **the trustworthiness of individuals is captured through endorsements by peers**. Endorsements act as **data points** that reflect an individual’s alignment with the proposed trust principles.

Traditional social media relies on weak endorsements—**likes**, **votes**, and **retweets**—prioritizing **quantity** over **quality**. These signals lose value rapidly; a **"like" today** is more valuable than one **tomorrow**, and within a **month**, it has lost all its **value**.

In contrast, our platform uses a **strong endorsement**: **“True.”** When users mark something as **“True,”** they put their **reputation** on the line, ensuring **thoughtful validation**. A **“True” endorsement** retains its value over time and can be **revoked** if views change.

Unlike fleeting likes, **“True” endorsement** carries the **reputation** of the validator, encouraging **accountability**. By rewarding **substance over superficiality**, the platform promotes **ethical actions**, fosters **trust**, and creates a **self-reinforcing system** where **trustworthiness** is visible and rewarded.

**We suggest that endorsements** are exclusively based on **rewards** and never on punishments. This is because positive **reinforcement** is more effective for shaping behavior (Skinner, 1953; Deci & Ryan, 1985). Studies show people respond better to **social rewards** like **praise, recognition, and validation** than to criticism or punishment (Cameron & Pierce, 1994). By **rewarding people for adherence to trust principles**, the system motivates individuals to act ethically without fear of retribution.

To ensure **accountability**, endorsements are **revocable**. If a user violates trust principles, their endorsements can be withdrawn, discouraging unethical behavior. This risk motivates users to act responsibly, as losing endorsements—especially from reputable individuals—harms their reputation. 

### Modified PageRank for Cognitive Trustworthiness {#modified-pagerank-for-cognitive-trustworthiness}

Inspired by the **PageRank algorithm** (Brin & Page, 1998), which ranks web pages by link quality and quantity, we use a similar approach: endorsements function like links, granting **reputational weight** to individuals demonstrating trust principles. Just as links from highly ranked pages increase value, endorsements from trustworthy individuals amplify others’ trustworthiness. This generates a **recursive network** where trustworthiness is calculated, similar to how PageRank identifies valuable web pages.

Unlike pure PageRank, the system leverages the **social graph** to **personalize trustworthiness scores**. Endorsements from **closer connections**—direct connections of the user or profiles with many validated authentic mutual connections—carry more weight. In contrast, endorsements from **distant or untrustworthy users** have minimal impact. This **“closeness discounting”** ensures scores are **contextually relevant** and reflect **relational dynamics**, improving **precision** and **relevance**.

The system promotes **decentralization**: no central authority determines trustworthiness. Instead, scores are **dynamically calculated** and personalized through the social graph. Each user’s trust network is unique, reflecting their **connections** and **relationships** rather than being imposed by a central entity. 

### Relationship Between Cognitive Trustworthiness and Memetic Fitness {#relationship-between-cognitive-trustworthiness-and-memetic-fitness}

**Posts** can include any content shared on the platform, such as articles, comments, or media. Users validate posts as **“True”**, **“False”**, or **“I don’t know”**, reflecting their perception of the **memetic fitness** of the ideas contained.

The **trustworthiness** of individuals—based on their adherence to **trust principles**—is crucial in determining the memetic fitness of their ideas. Posts endorsed by **trustworthy users** are ranked higher, linking the memetic **fitness of the idea** to the **trustworthiness scores** of its validators.

The combined **trustworthiness scores** of all validators determine the **memetic fitness** of the idea behind the post. This enables competing ideas to be compared through a **scalable system**, identifying content with **high memetic fitness** in a **decentralized way** without any central authority.

### Enabling Adoption Through Compatibility and Privacy {#enabling-adoption-through-compatibility-and-privacy}

We propose designing the **Authentic Networking Platform** with **backward compatibility** to existing social networks. This approach allows users to **import their connections, data, and activity**, reducing **barriers to entry** and easing the transition. By leveraging **existing social graphs**, the platform **reduces time-to-value** and accelerates user **adoption**. This strategy ensures a **smooth launch** and positions the platform for **rapid growth** in a **competitive landscape**.

**Privacy protection** is critical for establishing **backward compatibility** with existing social networks. This requires strict adherence to the **privacy policies of the original social networks**, respecting the privacy agreements users have already accepted. The privacy policies of social networks typically permit users to **see, copy, and process data** shared with them by other users, such as **names** and **emails**, within the limits of privacy settings. The **Authentic Networking Platform** must uphold this standard, allowing users to save and process only **explicitly permitted data**, ensuring compliance with laws like **GDPR** and the **EU Digital Markets Act**. By respecting original policies, the platform enables **secure interoperability** without compromising users' **privacy**.

## Trustworthiness and Memetic Fitness Algorithm {#trustworthiness-and-memetic-fitness-algorithm}

Below, we propose algorithms to calculate the **trustworthiness of an individual** and the **memetic fitness of their ideas**. **Endorsements on trust principles** act as weighted links within the **social graph**. An individual’s **trustworthiness** is calculated recursively, accounting for the **reputation** and **proximity** of endorsers. Similarly, the **memetic fitness of an idea** is determined by aggregating the **trustworthiness scores** of its validators. Notably, we have not yet specified how endorsements on the six separate **trust principles** can be consolidated into a single **trustworthiness score**, leaving this an open problem for future exploration.

# Discussion And Implications {#discussion-and-implications}

Our evolved capacity for morality and reasoning paradoxically fuels tribalism—favoring those with shared beliefs and excluding others. Novak's research on indirect reciprocity suggests using reputation systems to extend trust beyond tribal lines. 

However, until now, no framework has bridged morality and epistemology to measure trustworthiness. The **Intuitive Trust-Building Framework** fills this gap, addressing key challenges like the **Hard Problem of Cooperation**, the **Tragedy of the Commons**, and the **Tragedy of Rationality**. It explores why cooperation fails and offers a path to foster collaboration across personal, societal, and global divides.

We have not empirically measured how often people feel treated according to the **Golden Aspects** of trusted principles or how often they witness violations of the **Silver Rule**. However, in a world rife with mistrust, it’s reasonable to assume that **Golden treatment** is rare while violations occur daily. This gap between individual expectations and daily reality highlights the need to rebuild **trust**.

We derived six trust principles, each with a **Golden Aspect** for group insiders and a **Silver Aspect** for group outsiders. This graduated approach provides a practical **test of** **impartiality**: how far can an individual extend trust principles beyond her immediate group? 

The challenge of passing the **test of impartiality** lies in our tribal instincts—we naturally trust those who share our genes, beliefs, and culture. Extending trust to outsiders is risky; they might harm, deplete resources, or damage reputations. The framework addresses these risks with graduated trust, starting with **Silver Aspects** to establish mutual non-harm and progressing to **Golden Aspects** only for proven trustworthy outsiders.

## Moral Obligations: Scientific Method, Growth Mindset, and Debiasing  {#moral-obligations:-scientific-method,-growth-mindset,-and-debiasing}

The **scientific method**, **growth mindset** (introduced by **Carol Dweck** in 2006), and **debiasing** are often regarded as cognitive tools for success, commonly taught in universities or valued in professional settings. However, if one accepts that **Trust Principle 3**—**Intellectual Humility through Critical Thinking**—is grounded in the **Golden Rule**, these traits become moral responsibilities.

Once the connection between the **Golden Rule** and **Trust Principle 3** is understood, failing to adopt the **scientific method**, **growth mindset**, and **debiasing** leads to **cognitive dissonance**. Individuals face a clear choice: embrace **Intellectual Humility through Critical Thinking** as a moral obligation or reject the **Golden Rule** itself. Yet, rejecting the **Golden Rule** is rarely a public option due to its universal appeal.

This logical link provides a pathway to transform traditional cultures from within. Since the **Golden Rule** already forms the foundation of many cultures, it can be leveraged to help individuals pass the **test of impartiality** more effectively.

## Practical Considerations for Authentic Networking Platform  {#practical-considerations-for-authentic-networking-platform}

As we showed in the introduction, **trustworthiness is rarely rewarded** in many fields, including politics, banking, and multinational organizations. Worse, **untrustworthy individuals often succeed** by convincingly faking trustworthiness, putting genuinely trustworthy individuals at a disadvantage. This problem arises because **verifying trustworthiness is costly**.

We proposed the **Authentic Networking Platform** as a **cost-effective, reliable, and scalable solution** for measuring and validating trustworthiness. By reducing the validation cost, the platform will **make it harder to fake trustworthiness** while **incentivizing genuine ethical behavior**.

It seems reasonable that once validation becomes more accessible, **ethical behavior** will gain greater recognition, potentially reshaping environments where **untrustworthiness** thrives. Those who avoid the platform or fail to secure **endorsements** may face challenging questions, such as:

* *“Why don’t you have a profile on the Authentic Networking Platform?”*  
* *“Why don’t your ideas have gained validation by trustworthy individuals?”*  
* *“If you intend to keep your promises, why don’t you publish them on the platform?”*  
* *“If you think this idea is true, why don’t you validate it on the platform?”*  
* *“Why don’t your connections endorse you on trust principles?”*

Even without advanced algorithms, the platform’s **basic features** could still be practical. For example, users might be able to view endorsements from individuals who themselves have a **high number of endorsements**. Additionally, users could see endorsers with many **genuine mutual connections** first. We believe these features will significantly lower the cost of validating **trustworthiness**.

The platform could foster collective moral development by leveraging **Trust Principle 6 (Moral Development)**, encouraging users to empower others to adopt trust principles. This may create a **virality** effect, where participation spreads trust principles across the community. As more users join and engage, ethical integrity could become a community-driven value, promoting trust and accountability on a larger scale. If this viral growth occurs, it could lead to a self-reinforcing cycle, amplifying the platform’s impact in reshaping environments with greater trust.

## Resolving Epistemic Conflicts  {#resolving-epistemic-conflicts}

Popper’s principle of **falsifiability** has been fundamental to scientific progress, ensuring that theories can be tested and refuted (Popper, 1959). However, for non-experts, it presents two significant challenges: **shallow skepticism**, where people doubt everything indiscriminately and **misuse**, which is exploited to reject claims endlessly. These issues arise because claimants often **appear** equally trustworthy, and until now, there has been no reliable way to assess whether their trustworthiness is **genuine**.

Our framework builds on Popper’s ideas by introducing **Principle 3: Intellectual Humility through Critical Thinking**. Non-experts can ask a critical question: **"Who has made the most effort to falsify their ideas?"** The answer lies in identifying experts who are highly endorsed by other trustworthy experts for their commitment to Intellectual Humility and Critical Thinking. By highlighting and rewarding such efforts, our platform makes falsification more accessible to **real-world decision-making**, enabling non-experts to trust those with high-quality endorsements on trust principle 3\.

Once a critical mass of **users** and **endorsements** of posts and trusted principles is reached, the memetic fitness algorithm applied to the user feed will likely dramatically **reduce the cost** of discovering ideas with **high long-term memetic fitness**. Unlike **Wikipedia**, which focuses on **past knowledge**, this platform supports **future-oriented content**, **fact-checking**, and **large-scale coordination** on emerging issues. Furthermore, the platform will likely **lower the cost** of building **trust** among large groups of people who do not know each other personally. This will be achieved through the **revocability of endorsements**: if a user begins to act **untrustworthily**—such as engaging in **dogmatic thinking**, **breaking promises**, or **telling lies**—users who endorsed them will likely want to **revoke their endorsements** to protect their own **reputation**.

## Resolving Hierarchical Conflicts  {#resolving-hierarchical-conflicts}

While epistemic conflicts focus on **what is true**, hierarchical conflicts revolve around **who is in charge**—deciding who should lead or hold responsibility in a specific context. Our platform addresses hierarchical conflicts by proposing that the individual validated to be the **most trustworthy** should lead. One of the key implications of this approach is that it shifts decision-making from popularity or influence to **validated trustworthiness**. This creates a system where leadership is determined not by who is most visible or socially connected but by who consistently demonstrates trustworthiness through their actions and relationships. Over time, this method builds a more reliable foundation for hierarchical decision-making, strengthening trust at both individual and systemic levels.

## Evolution of Group Membership {#evolution-of-group-membership}

Groups traditionally form around shared beliefs, morals, or kinship. This creates inner cohesion but outer barriers. Extending **trustworthiness with moral and epistemic impartiality** offers a new path forward. By following universal **trust principles**, groups can transition from a similarity and sympathy-based approach to a membership definition based on **trustworthiness**. Trust-based groups don't replace traditional similarity or sympathy-based groups \- they enhance them.

David Sloan Wilson's **group selection theory** explains how groups with cooperative traits outperform others (Wilson, 2015). Therefore, groups that promote **trustworthiness** gain an **evolutionary** **advantage** through increased cooperation and inclusivity. Mutual trust enhances both individual problem-solving capacity and the group's collective fitness.

For instance, in bird flocks, individuals who cry out may risk predator attention, but when all participate, the group's survival improves. Similarly, by adhering to the derived **trust** **principles**, group members enhance their cooperation capacity with group insiders and outsiders. By adopting a **trust-building framework** for its members, a similarity-based group transitions into a trust-based group.

The **second-order public goods problem** (Ostrom, 1990\) arises when efforts to enforce cooperation, such as punishing free riders or encouraging contributions, become public goods themselves. While enforcing the punishment of free riders benefits the group as a whole, it requires effort and resources from individuals. This creates an additional challenge: How does a group ensure the punishment of free riders?

We propose that trust-based groups can use the **Authentic Networking Platform** to measure and consequently reward the **trustworthiness** of their members. Members who adhere to **trust principles** gain influence and standing within the group, while non-adherence can reduce credibility and social standing within the group. Using the Authentic Networking Platform, a trust-based group can enforce trustworthiness by rewarding those who adhere to trust principles and punishing those who fake trustworthiness.

Unlike traditional similarity-based groups, trust-based membership complements members' other group affiliations instead of conflicting with them. Members of trust-based groups enhance their value in other similarity-based groups to which they belong. For instance, individuals who develop **active** **listening** and **critical** **thinking** will be seen as more trustworthy collaborators in similarity-based groups, too. This creates a virtuous cycle: trust-based membership strengthens an individual's contributions across all their similarity-group affiliations.

## Future Directions {#future-directions}

### Interdisciplinary Collaboration, Empirical Validation, and Universal Agreement {#interdisciplinary-collaboration,-empirical-validation,-and-universal-agreement}

This paper is an *initial theoretical draft*, inviting feedback to improve the design of the **Intuitive** **Trust-Building** **Framework** and the **Authentic** **Networking** **Platform**. Effective feedback requires **collaboration** **across** **disciplines,** such as cognitive and moral psychology, ethics, economics, sociology, anthropology, and evolutionary biology.

**Workshops**, **pilot studies**, and **academic discussions** are essential for testing the paper's assumptions, methods, and proposed theoretical results. **Empirical validation** is critical to assess real-world applicability. While we believe that people across cultures will agree with all six statements involving Person A and Person B, their phrasing can improve for clarity and universal understanding. An empirical study could also reveal the **size of perceived gaps** between **expectations** and the **actual** trustworthiness of group insiders versus group outsiders across cultures.

**Controlled experiments** could measure how specific applications of the **Golden and Silver Aspects** of trusted principles influence conflict resolution. Based on these findings, cognitive psychologists could design **more efficient and cost-effective debiasing methods**. New debiasing methods will activate **System 1 thinking** to appeal intuitively rather than overriding it.

**Longitudinal studies** can evaluate whether applying the framework sustains **trust-building behaviors** and reduces biases over time. These methods would refine the framework and ensure **relevance across diverse contexts, cultures, geographies, and industries**.

Once **empirically validated**, this framework could provide a foundation for achieving **universal agreement on trusted principles**. Much like the **Universal Declaration of Human Rights** established shared ethical standards after World War II, this framework could unify diverse cultures and disciplines into a **Universal Trust-Building Framework**.

By offering **clear expectations** for interactions across cultures, universal agreement on trusted principles would address questions like, *"Why should I follow these principles?"* A universally recognized framework would demonstrate their **practical value** in fostering trust, reducing conflict, and enhancing cooperation. Grounded in its **intuitive appeal** and **cultural inclusivity**, it could support a more **cohesive and resilient global society**.

### Testing Theories with Simulations {#testing-theories-with-simulations}

We postulated that **trust-based groups** hold an evolutionary advantage over those built solely on **similarity**, **sympathy**, or **hierarchy**. This explanation challenges traditional views of group cohesion. Future work can test this postulate through **agent-based simulations** comparing trust-based and similarity-based groups under conditions like **resource scarcity** or **external threats** to the whole collective of groups. These models should evaluate the effectiveness of **trust-building behaviors** not only within the groups but also across groups and their impact on the **survival of individual groups and the collective of all groups**.

We proposed that observable **trust behaviors** reliably indicate the genuine **trustworthiness of individuals**. Future work could simulate interactions where agents demonstrate or fake these behaviors, examining their effects on **cooperation** and **conflict resolution** in **multicultural settings**. These simulations should explore conditions where such behaviors thrive or fail. In particular, one could ask if and how introducing a reliable, **cost-effective**, and **accessible trustworthiness measurement instrument** changes the environment.

We deduced that the **confidence-competence paradox** systematically misallocates trust, favoring confidence over competence and leading to inefficiencies. This insight connects directly to **systemic failures** in trust allocation. Future work could simulate scenarios where agents that vary in confidence and competence evolve when a **trustworthiness measurement instrument** is introduced into the environment.

We conjectured that **trust-optimized environments** enhance the spread of long-term **high-fitness ideas** while limiting the influence of long-term **low-fitness ones**. This conjecture forms the basis for improving idea quality in **social** and **informational networks**. Simulations could explore idea propagation in networks with and without **trust measurement instruments**, such as **peer validation** or **reputation systems**. We could test if trust measurement instruments help members of **trust-based groups** promote long-term, high-fitness ideas to spread and endure.

### Application Areas: Measurement, Training, and Investment {#application-areas:-measurement,-training,-and-investment}

If empirical studies confirm that **trust principles** hold **intuitive appeal across cultures**, it becomes essential to make **training** in the six trust behaviors more **accessible** and **adaptable**. The framework could guide the development of training in **active listening**, **critical thinking,** and **debiasing**, grounded in the **Golden** and **Silver Rules**.

In business, trust principles can improve **negotiations**, **hiring**, and **sales**. Negotiators unfamiliar with trust-based approaches could be guided to adopt these principles, leading to **better outcomes** and **mutual benefit**. Hiring processes could prioritize traits like **cognitive empathy**, **intellectual humility**, and **reliability**, streamlining evaluations. In sales, **transparent** and **consistent practices** help sellers build stronger relationships while enabling buyers to better assess **trustworthiness**, reducing risks and fostering **repeat business**. Embedding trust principles into core processes can improve **efficiency**, strengthen **partnerships**, and lead to **long-term success**.

Educational institutions can transform society by integrating trust principles into general **curricula**. **Active listening**, often taught in business but rarely in schools, could become a **foundational skill**. Religious organizations traditionally focused on promoting the **Golden** **Rule** could expand their role by connecting it to **critical thinking** and **debiasing**. Embedding these principles into **schools**, **spiritual communities**, and **workplaces** could enhance **education**, improve **interpersonal dynamics**, and strengthen **societal systems**.

The framework emphasizes the need to measure the **effectiveness** of programs, tools, training, or platforms—such as the **Authentic Networking Platform**—in helping individuals adopt **trusted behaviors**. Specifically, it is crucial to assess the **cost per measurable increase in trustworthiness**. This data would allow stakeholders to identify the most impactful and efficient methods for fostering trust-building behaviors.

Once we have created reliable instruments to measure trustworthiness, **governments**, **organizations**, **nonprofits**, and **private investors** can focus their resources on scaling the most **cost-effective solutions**. By understanding what works best, stakeholders can prioritize programs that maximize the adoption of behaviors aligned with the **Golden** and **Silver Rules**.

Investing in such initiatives could have a **multiplier effect**. Trustworthy individuals are more likely to inspire trust-building behaviors in others, creating a **ripple effect** that impacts not just individuals but also the **organizations**, **institutions**, and **societies** they interact with. This viral spread of trust principles could address systemic challenges like **misinformation**, **inequality**, and **climate change** while fostering collaboration and improving decision-making across sectors.

By focusing on **what to measure**—the effectiveness and cost-efficiency of trust-building methods—stakeholders can ensure their investments are grounded in evidence. This approach aligns with the principles of **effective altruism**, prioritizing initiatives with the highest return on investment for improving trustworthiness and driving broad societal change.

### Developing the Authentic Networking Platform {#developing-the-authentic-networking-platform}

We recommend developing the **Authentic Networking Platform** to operationalize the proposed **Intuitive Trust-Building Framework**. While we hope to inspire competition in this space, we are also committed to making progress ourselves.

As of December 2024, with **Inguro.com**, we have achieved a **problem-solution fit**. Our early adopters are **B2B service providers**. We have developed an **MVP**, obtained early user validation, generated initial revenue, and demonstrated evidence of helping early adopters gain referrals more efficiently. The platform already implements key features such as **backward compatibility with LinkedIn**, **privacy controls**, **network synchronization**, **validation of authentic connections**, **people search**, and specialized **chat functionality** for requesting partners to validate the authenticity of their connections. These features are particularly useful for improving referral effectiveness. Existing capabilities provide a strong foundation for expanding into a comprehensive, **Authentic Networking Platform**.

Our current focus is decreasing **time to value**, increasing **retention**, and proving **product-market fit**. Once this is achieved, we plan to invest in developing additional features outlined in this paper, including **profile sections** with revocable endorsements based on trust principles and mechanisms to create and validate posts as “true.” With broader user adoption and data, we aim to develop **trustworthiness** and **memetic fitness algorithms** to recommend **relevant and meaningful content** within user feeds.

We welcome **collaborations** and invite interested parties to submit proposals to contribute to the platform's development and refinement.

# Conclusion {#conclusion}

**Mistrust** is tearing at the fabric of our world, dividing societies, fueling conflict, and stifling progress. Challenges like **climate change**, **misinformation**, and **geopolitical tensions** demand an extraordinary response: **trust**. Without it, **cooperation collapses**, and humanity stagnates.

This work introduces the **Intuitive Trust-Building Framework** as a way forward. It addresses three root causes of the trust crisis—the **Hard Problem of Cooperation**, the **Tragedy of the Commons**, and the **Tragedy of Rationality**—and provides **actionable solutions**. Operationalizing **moral and epistemic impartiality** through **observable trust behaviors** ensures trustworthiness becomes **measurable**, **practical**, and **scalable**.

The **Authentic Networking Platform** brings these ideas to life. Leveraging **peer validation** of authentic connections and **endorsements** based on observable trust behaviors, the platform **deters manipulation**, **incentivizes genuine trust**, and **fosters global cooperation**.

The **framework** and **platform** can help us move toward a world where **trust is the default**. A world where more people globally follow the **Silver Rule**, preventing harm across divides, and the **Golden Rule**, fostering fairness and kindness. A world where **long-term high-fitness ideas** unite us instead of dividing us. In such a world, **trust-based groups** achieve more by cooperating effectively and rewarding integrity. The **Authentic Networking Platform** can accelerate this evolution.

Trust is **transformative**—it restores connection, inspires action, and unlocks shared purpose. A future without trust is one of **scarcity** and **despair**, while a future with trust unlocks **progress and possibility**.

We invite **researchers, innovators, and leaders** to refine and expand these principles, ensuring **trust** becomes the cornerstone of **human progress**. Together, we can create a world where trust thrives and enables **humanity's next significant step forward**.

# Attachment: Trust Traits, Behaviors and Principles  {#attachment:-trust-traits,-behaviors-and-principles}

|  | Trait | Behavior | Golden Aspect (In-Group) | Silver Aspect (Out-Group) | Epistemic grounding |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
| \#1 | Reliability | Promise-keeping | Keep promises, even when the personal cost is high. | Don’t make promises you intend to break. | Ensures consistent outcomes  |
| \#2 | Cognitive empathy | Active listening | Give people the feeling that you understand them, even when there are fundamental disagreements. | Don’t ignore the perspectives of others, even when there are fundamental disagreements. | Helps receive information with less noise |
| \#3 | Intellectual humility | Critical thinking | Actively search for arguments that could prove you wrong even when you feel right.  | Don’t ignore arguments that could prove you wrong even when you feel right. | Helps reduce errors in processing |
| \#4 | Honesty | Transparency | Tell the truth with kindness, even at a personal cost. | Avoid intentionally lying to advance your interests. | Enables feedback loops to correct errors |
| \#5 | Future Orientation | Long-term Thinking | Look decades ahead and consider the long-term effects of your actions | Don’t ignore the long-term effects of your actions | Prevents premature conclusions |
| \#6 | Moral character | Moral development | Empower people to treat others the way they would want to be treated themselves. | Help people avoid treating others in ways they would not want to be treated themselves. | Helps reduce the error rates of others |
